To open an iframe in a panel in JupyterLab in response to a command, you can create a custom extension that uses the JupyterLab API to define the command and panel, and then dynamically open the iframe in that panel when the command is triggered.

Here’s a simple outline of how you might structure this in your JupyterLab extension:

### 1. Define the Command

In your `index.ts` or main extension file, you can define a command that, when triggered, will open the iframe in a new panel.

```typescript
import {
  JupyterFrontEnd,
  JupyterFrontEndPlugin,
} from '@jupyterlab/application';
import { CommandRegistry } from '@phosphor/commands';
import { Widget } from '@phosphor/widgets';
import { IFrame } from '@jupyterlab/apputils';

const iframeCommand: JupyterFrontEndPlugin<void> = {
  id: 'iframe-command',
  autoStart: true,
  activate: (app: JupyterFrontEnd) => {
    const { commands } = app;
    commands.addCommand('iframe-command:open', {
      label: 'Open Iframe in Panel',
      execute: () => {
        openIframePanel(app);
      },
    });
  },
};

function openIframePanel(app: JupyterFrontEnd) {
  const iframeWidget = new IFrame();
  iframeWidget.url = 'https://your-iframe-url.com'; // Replace with your iframe URL

  // Create a new panel and add the iframe widget
  const panel = app.shell.add(iframeWidget, 'main');
  panel.title.label = 'Iframe Panel';
  panel.title.closable = true;
}

export default iframeCommand;
```

### 2. Register the Command

Ensure that you register your command in the extension's main plugin file:

```typescript
import iframeCommand from './iframe-command';

const extension: JupyterFrontEndPlugin<void> = {
  id: 'your-extension-id',
  autoStart: true,
  activate: (app: JupyterFrontEnd) => {
    app.commands.addCommand('iframe-command:open', {
      label: 'Open Iframe in Panel',
      execute: () => {
        openIframePanel(app);
      },
    });
  },
};

export default extension;
```

### 3. Bind the Command to a Button or Keybinding

If you want to trigger the command with a button or keybinding, you can add that to the UI in your extension as well.

For a button:
```typescript
const button = new Widget();
button.node.textContent = 'Open Iframe';
button.node.onclick = () => app.commands.execute('iframe-command:open');
```

For a keybinding, you can add a keybinding in the `activate` function:
```typescript
app.commands.addKeyBinding({
  command: 'iframe-command:open',
  keys: ['Ctrl Shift I'],
  selector: 'body',
});
```

### 4. Install and Build the Extension

Make sure to install the necessary dependencies and build your extension with `npm run build` or `yarn build`, depending on your setup.

### Result
This will open the iframe in a new panel within JupyterLab when the command `iframe-command:open` is executed. You can trigger this command with a button, keybinding, or by any other UI interaction you prefer.

